{
  "texts": [
    "Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) addresses knowledge gaps in large language models (LLMs) by retrieving external information at inference time (Lewis et al., 2020).",
    "While effective, RAG's performance depends heavily on retrieval quality; irrelevant documents can mislead the model and degrade the quality of its output (Cho et al., 2023; Shi et al., 2023).",
    "For example, when asked \"Who painted Starry Night?\"",
    "a naive retriever may surface a general Wikipedia article on Post-Impressionism rather than the specific page on Vincent van Gogh, offering little direct evidence for the correct answer.",
    "This issue becomes more pronounced in multi-hop QA tasks, where supporting facts are spread across multiple documents."
  ]
}